To fit a model, we need to select a functional form

model(p4sr) <- ricker()

so p4sr is all set up

model formula

model(p4sr)
## rec ~ a * ssb * exp(-b * ssb)
## <environment: 0x5799288>

log-likelihood function

logl(p4sr)
## function (a, b, rec, ssb) 
## loglAR1(log(rec), log(a * ssb * exp(-b * ssb)))
## <environment: 0x5799288>

initial values function

initial(p4sr)
## function (rec, ssb) 
## {
##     res <- coefficients(lm(log(c(rec)/c(ssb)) ~ c(ssb)))
##     return(FLPar(a = max(exp(res[1])), b = -max(res[2])))
## }
## <environment: 0x5799288>
## attr(,"lower")
## [1] -Inf -Inf
## attr(,"upper")
## [1] Inf Inf

and ouputs: params

params(p4sr)

p4sr <- fmle(p4sr, method='L-BFGS-B')
## final  value -21.363701

The nhser dataset is perfect for FLSR

data(nsher)
plot(ssb(nsher), rec(nsher))

There are also other SR models to choose from

## $logl
## function (a, b, c, rec, ssb) 
## loglAR1(log(rec), log(a * ssb/(1 + (ssb/b)^c)))

## <environment: 0x4b0eea0>

##     x <- ssb^c
